# mix deps.audit --ignore-file .deps_audit_ignore
#
# GHSA-52mm-h59v-f3c7 - earmark: Stored XSS via unescaped HTML attribute values
# earmark is retired/unmaintained upstream with no patched release available
# (fix would require migrating to MDEx). The only call site
# (lib/melocoton_web/live/sql_live/ai_chat_component.ex) already pipes
# Earmark output through HtmlSanitizeEx.markdown_html() before marking it
# raw, which strips the unescaped attribute values this advisory exploits.
# Additionally, melocoton runs as a single-user desktop app rather than a
# multi-user web service, so there's no cross-user/session boundary for a
# stored XSS payload to cross.
GHSA-52mm-h59v-f3c7

# GHSA-gp9c-pm5m-5cxr, GHSA-j9wq-vxxc-94wf, GHSA-mp55-p8c9-rfw2,
# GHSA-pj7v-xfvx-wmjq - hackney (transitive dep of testcontainers, dev/test
# only via `only: [:dev, :test]` in mix.exs).
# testcontainers pins `hackney ~> 1.20` (confirmed still true on its
# unreleased main branch), and hackney's last 1.x release, 1.25.0, has no
# patched build - the fix required jumping to 4.0.1+. Overriding to
# hackney 4.x was tried and broke Testcontainers' Docker-socket detection
# in CI (DockerUrl.test_docker_host/1 hardcodes Tesla.Adapter.Hackney to
# probe the unix socket, and something in that path regressed across the
# 1.x -> 4.x rewrite), so it was reverted. All four advisories concern
# hackney acting as an HTTP client against attacker-influenced URLs
# (CRLF/SSRF/TLS timeout); testcontainers only uses hackney to talk to the
# local Docker daemon over a unix socket with a URL it constructs itself,
# so there's no untrusted input reaching hackney here.
GHSA-gp9c-pm5m-5cxr
GHSA-j9wq-vxxc-94wf
GHSA-mp55-p8c9-rfw2
GHSA-pj7v-xfvx-wmjq
